While the Stash upgrade guide does mention *server.xml*, it doesn't mention HTTPS proxy, which is a common customization:

https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Stash+upgrade+guide#Stashupgradeguide-Upgradesteps

{quote}
You may have made changes to the port, context path, and/or access protocol (conf/server.xml).
{quote}

It would be nice to have that doc edited and the information added.

If someone installed new plugin or changed (updated) old one, or disabled/enabled/unistalled — in all cases Stash can send email notification to System Admin.
{code}
The plugin 'Scm Cache' was installed, updated, enabled, disabled, uninstalled by `login`.

Old version of plugin: 1.0
New version of plugin: 1.2
{code}

For instance:
{noformat}
curl -H "Content-Type:application/json" -H "Accept:application/json" --user admin:admin -X GET 'http://localhost:7990/projects/TEST/repos/repotest3/changes?since=e508f7a&until=4d15880&start=0&limit=100000'
{noformat}
This returns to me:
{noformat}
{"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/TEST/repos/repotest3/commits/4d15880#File817.txt"}]}}],"size":1000,"isLastPage":false,"start":0,"limit":100000,"nextPageStart":100000}
{noformat}

Notice that this parameter should be true: {{"isLastPage":false}} because the limit of 1000 was reached by currently respecting {{page.max.changes}} (this limit might change depending on the implementation of https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/STASH-5328)

"nextPageStart" is incorrect in this case - it should be {{null}}.

If you look at merge commits, it is difficult to get an idea of what was merged when all commits look like this:

{quote}
Merge pull request #N in project/repository from user/repository:branch into master.
Merge pull request #K in project/repository from user/repository:branch into master.
Merge pull request #J in project/repository from user/repository:branch into master.
{quote}

I have no problem with making this a default merge commit message, but I'd like to override it so I can see messages like:

{quote}
Fixes issue #N.
Adds feature XYZ.
...
{quote}

Currently it accepts a path component (where "api", which houses Stash's core REST APIs, is the default), but this is [undocumented|https://developer.atlassian.com/stash/docs/latest/reference/javascript/navbuilder_.html#rest]. It should also accept a version string to use in place of "latest".

E.g.
{code}
require(['stash/api/util/navbuilder'], function(navbuilder) {
    var url = navbuilder.rest('my-rest-things', '2.0')
            .addPathComponents('a', 'b')
            .build();
    console.log(url); // /stash/rest/my-rest-things/2.0/a/b
});
{code}

When using "Default Group Memberships" to assign LDAP users to a group with a minimal [Global Permission|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Global+permissions] within Stash, as users from LDAP login into Stash and are assigned to the default group, thus consuming a license (consider Stash is licensed for "N" users), instead of denying access to the "N-th +1" user, it allows the user to login and server blocks pull/push as described on https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/STASH-4643 and the message below is displayed:
{noformat}
You have more users than your license allows. Pushing is disabled - purchase a license today
{noformat}

Stash shouldn't allow a user to login and get added to the default group in such use case.

The link markdown creates an extra slash in the URL if just an anchor is used. This causes the anchor link not to jump to the appropriate anchor on the page until it's clicked a second time. The behavior is also different from how Bitbucket markdown creates the link.

*Stash*

{code}[connect](#connect){code}

Produces:
{{http://SERVER:7990/projects/PROJ/repos/REPO/browse/#connect}}

The resulting link should be:

{{http://SERVER:7990/projects/PROJ/repos/REPO/browse#connect}}

*Bitbucket*

{code}[connect](#connect){code}

Produces:
{{https://bitbucket.org/USERNAME/REPO/overview#connect}}

*Workaround*

{code}[connect](../browse#connect){code}

Our [SVN Mirror|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/plugins/org.tmatesoft.subgit.stash-svn-importer] add-on heavily relies on [pre-receive hook modules|https://developer.atlassian.com/stash/docs/3.0.1/reference/plugin-module-types/pre-receive-hook-plugin-module.html]. At the moment ordering of such hooks is non-deterministic:

{quote}
When writing hooks keep in mind that the ordering of the hooks is non-deterministic, and shouldn't be relied on. Passing state between hooks of the same type is fraught with danger and should not be attempted; each hook should be completely standalone.
{quote}

Unfortunately, that leads to unpredictable behavior for established Git-SVN mirrors. If SVN Mirror hook is getting triggered before other hooks, the result of those hooks is getting ignored, i.e. even if those hooks reject push operation, our hook still apply pushed commits as they already get synchronized with SVN server.

Is there any chance to provide any ordering mechanism for pre-receive hook modules?

